Stable Priorities for Fragile States
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared from the repercussions of COVID-19.
However, the world's most "fragile" states are facing a set of particularly complex problems.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already struggling with poverty, conflicts, corruption, and inefficient public administration.
Today, these factors leave these countries ill-equipped to handle the COVID-19 crisis.
The thing each country needs to cross the pandemic is precisely what fragile states lack: a state apparatus capable of developing and implementing an action plan, an effective police force to enforce the rules, social programs that provide funding, supplies, as well as health services to treat infected people.
The lack of means of the state is immediately felt in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions in Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
The Mali has only three ventilators for the entire country.
A effective response also relies on trust in the state's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states hardly benefits from the consent of the population.
In countries that are recovering from a conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, several people will refrain from supporting the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an indispensable component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to help those who cannot do so.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not present enough to meet these needs.
Earlier during the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the demographic weight of the young and geographical distance.
However, from our point of view as co-presidents of the new Council on State Fragility, it is a fact that this was not the case.
In the last few weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen all had infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries that were first hit by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more significant for fragile states. These will not only be the result of national lockdowns, but also of what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries such as China has dwindled, expatriate remittances have fallen, basic commodity prices and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are accumulating.
Since fragile states rely on imports for the majority of their food intake, we are increasingly talking about "hunger" and even "famine".
We should now understand that the problems of less fortunate countries have become, for the most part, global problems, whether in the form of massive migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the impoverished populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will only worsen.
That is why the Council on State Fragility has made it its absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges that these countries must face.
The council, composed of former world leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, and development organization presidents, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. It will aim to guide national and international policymakers on how fragile states will get out of this crisis and tackle their broader and deeper problems.
Decentralization, adaptability, and wise use of data will be essential.
For example, it is widely proven that "targeted confinement" of local outbreaks is often more suitable than national confinement.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency fades.
We propose five recommendations.
Firstly, access to social protection should be simpler and faster.
At times, this will be synonymous with universal eligibility rather than a precise targeting.
Mobile phone networks should be utilized in order to collect information on immediate needs and disburse small regular payments (although of limited duration).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which cultivated rice, has become increasingly dependent over the past decades.
Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land in general.
Local production initiatives for staple crops must be quickly deployed on a much broader scale.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production is launched, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate for and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, fragile states' businesses need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved financial institutions in international development; small businesses in less affluent countries are often neglected and suffering from the detrimental consequences of broader targets and rules (since it is easier to achieve a target by investing in large-scale projects in larger economies).
However, it is precisely these small businesses that need more significant investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is expected that countries receiving bilateral development aid must repay approximately 40 billion dollars to private and public creditors this year alone.
To prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to suspend accumulated debt not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
Furthermore, it is crucial that all fragile states obtain emergency funding to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions — particularly countries that do not normally have access to funding from the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund.
COVID-19 will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts promptly, we can mitigate the worst repercussions of the pandemic.
If there's one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it's that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
